NT|^B@2 
^*Bhondo717:^*N Now, back to aggie's responsibilities. There is a concept known as "captain" of the bidding. During most auctions, one of the partners is the "captain" and the other is the "subordinate." At the risk of sounding sexist, it turns out in most co-ed partnerships, the male always wants to be the "captain" and the "female" the subordinate :). Sad but true.|
PG| ***** 25 ***** |


NT|^B@2
^*Bhondo717:^*N However, if you want to play good bridge, that is not how it should be. Typically, responder is the captain. The captain is responsible for placing the final contract. The captain asks the subordinate questions, via the bidding, and the subordinate answers them. For example, on this hand, aggie should notice she has an invitational hand and she wants to be in game if kia has an intermediate or better hand, 15 or more points. |
PG| ***** 26 ***** |


NT|^B@2
^*Bhondo717:^*N The main bidding weapon the responder/captain has, is making forcing bids. New suit by responder is always forcing. In this hand, aggie needs to find out two things. First, what suit (or NT) should the hand be played in and second, whether or not to be in game. In this sequence, once kia bids diamonds and spades, it is clear they should be in NT. Now aggie knows they should be in NT, the question is what level. Since kia did not jump shift to 2@S, he can have 17 points at most, however, he could have as little as 12 points.|
PG| ***** 27 ***** |


NT|^B@2
^*Bhondo717:^*N aggie has to find out if kia is at the top of his range or not. If she has an opening hand, she should just bid 3N. With a minimum hand, she can bid 1N (6-9), and then, if kia has 17 or a good 16, it is up to him to go on. However, if she has an in-between hand, as a 11-12 points. she must tell kia , by bidding 2N, she has an in between hand and leave the final decision to him.|at|
