^C@2nome: As added emphasis on Howard's teaching I have decided each week to collect many of his @E@3important instructions in one page under "Howard's Pearls" which we can go over them many times. The following are my picks. I am sure you will find many more.|fp|2|at|

If you are an unpassed hand, a takeout double in direct seat pretty much guarantees an opening hand. It also pretty much guarantees 4 cards in the unbid major.

Carefully listen to the auction. It often gives you many clues about the hands.

If you can beat the contract, it is ok to play 2nd hand high.

Over opponent's takeout double, here is what is usually played:

1) One level bids are forcing one round, retaining the same meaning as if there was no takeout double (at least six points, but can be unlimited).

2) Two level bids show 5+ card suits, and deny 10 points.

3) Redouble with 10 or more points, and no appropriate one level bid.

4) Some people play Jordan 2N, where a 2N bid shows 10+ points and 4 card support for opener's suit (e.g. a limit raise).


